Functional Suitability.description: Degree to which a product or system provides functions that meet stated and implied needs when used under specified conditions

Performance Efficiency.description: Performance relative to the amount of resources used under stated conditions

Usability.description: Degree to which a product or system can be used by specified users to achieve specified goals with effectiveness, efficiency and satisfaction in a specified context of use

Compatibility.description: Degree to which a product, system or component can exchange information with other products, systems or components, and/or perform its required functions, while sharing the same hardware or software environment

Reliability.description: Degree to which a system, product or component performs specified functions under specified conditions for a specified period of time

Security.description: Degree to which a product or system protects information and data so that persons or other products or systems have the degree of data access appropriate to their types and levels of authorization

Maintainability.description: Degree of effectiveness and efficiency with which a product or system can be modified by the intended maintainers

Portability.description: degree of effectiveness and efficiency with which a system, product or component can be transferred from one hardware, software or other operational or usage environment to another

Base CWE-15.name: External Control of System or Configuration Setting
Base CWE-15.description: One or more system settings or configuration elements can be externally controlled by a user.

Base CWE-22.name: Improper Limitation of a Pathname to a Restricted Directory ('Path Traversal')
Base CWE-22.description: The product uses external input to construct a pathname that is intended to identify a file or directory that is located underneath a restricted parent directory, but the product does not properly neutralize special elements within the pathname that can cause the pathname to resolve to a location that is outside of the restricted directory.

Base CWE-41.name: Improper Resolution of Path Equivalence
Base CWE-41.description: The product is vulnerable to file system contents disclosure through path equivalence. Path equivalence involves the use of special characters in file and directory names. The associated manipulations are intended to generate multiple names for the same object.

Base CWE-59.name: Improper Link Resolution Before File Access ('Link Following')
Base CWE-59.description: The product attempts to access a file based on the filename, but it does not properly prevent that filename from identifying a link or shortcut that resolves to an unintended resource.

Base CWE-66.name: Improper Handling of File Names that Identify Virtual Resources
Base CWE-66.description: The product does not handle or incorrectly handles a file name that identifies a virtual resource that is not directly specified within the directory that is associated with the file name, causing the product to perform file-based operations on a resource that is not a file.

Base CWE-73.name: External Control of File Name or Path
Base CWE-73.description: The product allows user input to control or influence paths or file names that are used in filesystem operations.

Base CWE-76.name: Improper Neutralization of Equivalent Special Elements
Base CWE-76.description: The product correctly neutralizes certain special elements, but it improperly neutralizes equivalent special elements.

Base CWE-78.name: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an OS Command ('OS Command Injection')
Base CWE-78.description: The product constructs all or part of an OS command using externally-influenced input from an upstream component, but it does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes special elements that could modify the intended OS command when it is sent to a downstream component.

Base CWE-79.name: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')
Base CWE-79.description: The product does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes user-controllable input before it is placed in output that is used as a web page that is served to other users.

Base CWE-88.name: Improper Neutralization of Argument Delimiters in a Command ('Argument Injection')
Base CWE-88.description: The product constructs a string for a command to be executed by a separate component in another control sphere, but it does not properly delimit the intended arguments, options, or switches within that command string.

Base CWE-89.name: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')
Base CWE-89.description: The product constructs all or part of an SQL command using externally-influenced input from an upstream component, but it does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes special elements that could modify the intended SQL command when it is sent to a downstream component.

Base CWE-90.name: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an LDAP Query ('LDAP Injection')
Base CWE-90.description: The product constructs all or part of an LDAP query using externally-influenced input from an upstream component, but it does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes special elements that could modify the intended LDAP query when it is sent to a downstream component.

Base CWE-91.name: XML Injection (aka Blind XPath Injection)
Base CWE-91.description: The product does not properly neutralize special elements that are used in XML, allowing attackers to modify the syntax, content, or commands of the XML before it is processed by an end system.

Base CWE-93.name: Improper Neutralization of CRLF Sequences ('CRLF Injection')
Base CWE-93.description: The product uses CRLF (carriage return line feeds) as a special element, e.g. to separate lines or records, but it does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes CRLF sequences from inputs.

Base CWE-94.name: Improper Control of Generation of Code ('Code Injection')
Base CWE-94.description: The product constructs all or part of a code segment using externally-influenced input from an upstream component, but it does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes special elements that could modify the syntax or behavior of the intended code segment.

Base CWE-112.name: Missing XML Validation
Base CWE-112.description: The product accepts XML from an untrusted source but does not validate the XML against the proper schema.

Base CWE-115.name: Misinterpretation of Input
Base CWE-115.description: The product misinterprets an input, whether from an attacker or another product, in a security-relevant fashion.

Base CWE-117.name: Improper Output Neutralization for Logs
Base CWE-117.description: The product does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes output that is written to logs.

Base CWE-120.name: Buffer Copy without Checking Size of Input ('Classic Buffer Overflow')
Base CWE-120.description: The product copies an input buffer to an output buffer without verifying that the size of the input buffer is less than the size of the output buffer, leading to a buffer overflow.

Base CWE-124.name: Buffer Underwrite ('Buffer Underflow')
Base CWE-124.description: The product writes to a buffer using an index or pointer that references a memory location prior to the beginning of the buffer.

Base CWE-125.name: Out-of-bounds Read
Base CWE-125.description: The product reads data past the end, or before the beginning, of the intended buffer.

Base CWE-128.name: Wrap-around Error
Base CWE-128.description: Wrap around errors occur whenever a value is incremented past the maximum value for its type and therefore wraps around to a very small, negative, or undefined value.

Base CWE-130.name: Improper Handling of Length Parameter Inconsistency
Base CWE-130.description: The product parses a formatted message or structure, but it does not handle or incorrectly handles a length field that is inconsistent with the actual length of the associated data.

Base CWE-131.name: Incorrect Calculation of Buffer Size
Base CWE-131.description: The product does not correctly calculate the size to be used when allocating a buffer, which could lead to a buffer overflow.

Base CWE-134.name: Use of Externally-Controlled Format String
Base CWE-134.description: The product uses a function that accepts a format string as an argument, but the format string originates from an external source.

Base CWE-135.name: Incorrect Calculation of Multi-Byte String Length
Base CWE-135.description: The product does not correctly calculate the length of strings that can contain wide or multi-byte characters.

Base CWE-140.name: Improper Neutralization of Delimiters
Base CWE-140.description: The product does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes delimiters.

Base CWE-166.name: Improper Handling of Missing Special Element
Base CWE-166.description: The product receives input from an upstream component, but it does not handle or incorrectly handles when an expected special element is missing.

Base CWE-167.name: Improper Handling of Additional Special Element
Base CWE-167.description: The product receives input from an upstream component, but it does not handle or incorrectly handles when an additional unexpected special element is provided.

Base CWE-168.name: Improper Handling of Inconsistent Special Elements
Base CWE-168.description: The product does not properly handle input in which an inconsistency exists between two or more special characters or reserved words.

Base CWE-170.name: Improper Null Termination
Base CWE-170.description: The product does not terminate or incorrectly terminates a string or array with a null character or equivalent terminator.

Base CWE-178.name: Improper Handling of Case Sensitivity
Base CWE-178.description: The product does not properly account for differences in case sensitivity when accessing or determining the properties of a resource, leading to inconsistent results.

Base CWE-179.name: Incorrect Behavior Order: Early Validation
Base CWE-179.description: The product validates input before applying protection mechanisms that modify the input, which could allow an attacker to bypass the validation via dangerous inputs that only arise after the modification.

Base CWE-182.name: Collapse of Data into Unsafe Value
Base CWE-182.description: The product filters data in a way that causes it to be reduced or collapsed into an unsafe value that violates an expected security property.

Base CWE-183.name: Permissive List of Allowed Inputs
Base CWE-183.description: The product implements a protection mechanism that relies on a list of inputs (or properties of inputs) that are explicitly allowed by policy because the inputs are assumed to be safe, but the list is too permissive - that is, it allows an input that is unsafe, leading to resultant weaknesses.

Base CWE-184.name: Incomplete List of Disallowed Inputs
Base CWE-184.description: The product implements a protection mechanism that relies on a list of inputs (or properties of inputs) that are not allowed by policy or otherwise require other action to neutralize before additional processing takes place, but the list is incomplete, leading to resultant weaknesses.

Base CWE-186.name: Overly Restrictive Regular Expression
Base CWE-186.description: A regular expression is overly restrictive, which prevents dangerous values from being detected.

Base CWE-190.name: Integer Overflow or Wraparound
Base CWE-190.description: The product performs a calculation that can produce an integer overflow or wraparound, when the logic assumes that the resulting value will always be larger than the original value. This can introduce other weaknesses when the calculation is used for resource management or execution control.

Base CWE-191.name: Integer Underflow (Wrap or Wraparound)
Base CWE-191.description: The product subtracts one value from another, such that the result is less than the minimum allowable integer value, which produces a value that is not equal to the correct result.

Base CWE-193.name: Off-by-one Error
Base CWE-193.description: A product calculates or uses an incorrect maximum or minimum value that is 1 more, or 1 less, than the correct value.

Base CWE-201.name: Insertion of Sensitive Information Into Sent Data
Base CWE-201.description: The code transmits data to another actor, but a portion of the data includes sensitive information that should not be accessible to that actor.

Base CWE-204.name: Observable Response Discrepancy
Base CWE-204.description: The product provides different responses to incoming requests in a way that reveals internal state information to an unauthorized actor outside of the intended control sphere.

Base CWE-205.name: Observable Behavioral Discrepancy
Base CWE-205.description: The product's behaviors indicate important differences that may be observed by unauthorized actors in a way that reveals (1) its internal state or decision process, or (2) differences from other products with equivalent functionality.

Base CWE-208.name: Observable Timing Discrepancy
Base CWE-208.description: Two separate operations in a product require different amounts of time to complete, in a way that is observable to an actor and reveals security-relevant information about the state of the product, such as whether a particular operation was successful or not.

Base CWE-209.name: Generation of Error Message Containing Sensitive Information
Base CWE-209.description: The product generates an error message that includes sensitive information about its environment, users, or associated data.

Base CWE-212.name: Improper Removal of Sensitive Information Before Storage or Transfer
Base CWE-212.description: The product stores, transfers, or shares a resource that contains sensitive information, but it does not properly remove that information before the product makes the resource available to unauthorized actors.

Base CWE-213.name: Exposure of Sensitive Information Due to Incompatible Policies
Base CWE-213.description: The product's intended functionality exposes information to certain actors in accordance with the developer's security policy, but this information is regarded as sensitive according to the intended security policies of other stakeholders such as the product's administrator, users, or others whose information is being processed.

Base CWE-214.name: Invocation of Process Using Visible Sensitive Information
Base CWE-214.description: A process is invoked with sensitive command-line arguments, environment variables, or other elements that can be seen by other processes on the operating system.

Base CWE-215.name: Insertion of Sensitive Information Into Debugging Code
Base CWE-215.description: The product inserts sensitive information into debugging code, which could expose this information if the debugging code is not disabled in production.

Base CWE-222.name: Truncation of Security-relevant Information
Base CWE-222.description: The product truncates the display, recording, or processing of security-relevant information in a way that can obscure the source or nature of an attack.

Base CWE-223.name: Omission of Security-relevant Information
Base CWE-223.description: The product does not record or display information that would be important for identifying the source or nature of an attack, or determining if an action is safe.

Base CWE-224.name: Obscured Security-relevant Information by Alternate Name
Base CWE-224.description: The product records security-relevant information according to an alternate name of the affected entity, instead of the canonical name.

Base CWE-229.name: Improper Handling of Values
Base CWE-229.description: The product does not properly handle when the expected number of values for parameters, fields, or arguments is not provided in input, or if those values are undefined.

Base CWE-233.name: Improper Handling of Parameters
Base CWE-233.description: The product does not properly handle when the expected number of parameters, fields, or arguments is not provided in input, or if those parameters are undefined.

Base CWE-237.name: Improper Handling of Structural Elements
Base CWE-237.description: The product does not handle or incorrectly handles inputs that are related to complex structures.

Base CWE-241.name: Improper Handling of Unexpected Data Type
Base CWE-241.description: The product does not handle or incorrectly handles when a particular element is not the expected type, e.g. it expects a digit (0-9) but is provided with a letter (A-Z).

Base CWE-242.name: Use of Inherently Dangerous Function
Base CWE-242.description: The product calls a function that can never be guaranteed to work safely.

Variant CWE-243.name: Creation of chroot Jail Without Changing Working Directory
Variant CWE-243.description: The product uses the chroot() system call to create a jail, but does not change the working directory afterward. This does not prevent access to files outside of the jail.

Base CWE-248.name: Uncaught Exception
Base CWE-248.description: An exception is thrown from a function, but it is not caught.

Base CWE-250.name: Execution with Unnecessary Privileges
Base CWE-250.description: The product performs an operation at a privilege level that is higher than the minimum level required, which creates new weaknesses or amplifies the consequences of other weaknesses.

Base CWE-252.name: Unchecked Return Value
Base CWE-252.description: The product does not check the return value from a method or function, which can prevent it from detecting unexpected states and conditions.

Base CWE-253.name: Incorrect Check of Function Return Value
Base CWE-253.description: The product incorrectly checks a return value from a function, which prevents it from detecting errors or exceptional conditions.

Base CWE-256.name: Plaintext Storage of a Password
Base CWE-256.description: Storing a password in plaintext may result in a system compromise.

Base CWE-257.name: Storing Passwords in a Recoverable Format
Base CWE-257.description: The storage of passwords in a recoverable format makes them subject to password reuse attacks by malicious users. In fact, it should be noted that recoverable encrypted passwords provide no significant benefit over plaintext passwords since they are subject not only to reuse by malicious attackers but also by malicious insiders. If a system administrator can recover a password directly, or use a brute force search on the available information, the administrator can use the password on other accounts.

Base CWE-260.name: Password in Configuration File
Base CWE-260.description: The product stores a password in a configuration file that might be accessible to actors who do not know the password.

Base CWE-261.name: Weak Encoding for Password
Base CWE-261.description: Obscuring a password with a trivial encoding does not protect the password.

Base CWE-262.name: Not Using Password Aging
Base CWE-262.description: The product does not have a mechanism in place for managing password aging.

Base CWE-263.name: Password Aging with Long Expiration
Base CWE-263.description: The product supports password aging, but the expiration period is too long.

Base CWE-266.name: Incorrect Privilege Assignment
Base CWE-266.description: A product incorrectly assigns a privilege to a particular actor, creating an unintended sphere of control for that actor.

Base CWE-267.name: Privilege Defined With Unsafe Actions
Base CWE-267.description: A particular privilege, role, capability, or right can be used to perform unsafe actions that were not intended, even when it is assigned to the correct entity.

Base CWE-268.name: Privilege Chaining
Base CWE-268.description: Two distinct privileges, roles, capabilities, or rights can be combined in a way that allows an entity to perform unsafe actions that would not be allowed without that combination.

Base CWE-270.name: Privilege Context Switching Error
Base CWE-270.description: The product does not properly manage privileges while it is switching between different contexts that have different privileges or spheres of control.

Base CWE-272.name: Least Privilege Violation
Base CWE-272.description: The elevated privilege level required to perform operations such as chroot() should be dropped immediately after the operation is performed.

Base CWE-273.name: Improper Check for Dropped Privileges
Base CWE-273.description: The product attempts to drop privileges but does not check or incorrectly checks to see if the drop succeeded.

Base CWE-274.name: Improper Handling of Insufficient Privileges
Base CWE-274.description: The product does not handle or incorrectly handles when it has insufficient privileges to perform an operation, leading to resultant weaknesses.

Base CWE-276.name: Incorrect Default Permissions
Base CWE-276.description: During installation, installed file permissions are set to allow anyone to modify those files.

Variant CWE-277.name: Insecure Inherited Permissions
Variant CWE-277.description: A product defines a set of insecure permissions that are inherited by objects that are created by the program.

Variant CWE-278.name: Insecure Preserved Inherited Permissions
Variant CWE-278.description: A product inherits a set of insecure permissions for an object, e.g. when copying from an archive file, without user awareness or involvement.

Variant CWE-279.name: Incorrect Execution-Assigned Permissions
Variant CWE-279.description: While it is executing, the product sets the permissions of an object in a way that violates the intended permissions that have been specified by the user.

Base CWE-280.name: Improper Handling of Insufficient Permissions or Privileges
Base CWE-280.description: The product does not handle or incorrectly handles when it has insufficient privileges to access resources or functionality as specified by their permissions. This may cause it to follow unexpected code paths that may leave the product in an invalid state.

Base CWE-281.name: Improper Preservation of Permissions
Base CWE-281.description: The product does not preserve permissions or incorrectly preserves permissions when copying, restoring, or sharing objects, which can cause them to have less restrictive permissions than intended.

Base CWE-283.name: Unverified Ownership
Base CWE-283.description: The product does not properly verify that a critical resource is owned by the proper entity.

Base CWE-289.name: Authentication Bypass by Alternate Name
Base CWE-289.description: The product performs authentication based on the name of a resource being accessed, or the name of the actor performing the access, but it does not properly check all possible names for that resource or actor.

Base CWE-290.name: Authentication Bypass by Spoofing
Base CWE-290.description: This attack-focused weakness is caused by incorrectly implemented authentication schemes that are subject to spoofing attacks.

Base CWE-294.name: Authentication Bypass by Capture-replay
Base CWE-294.description: A capture-replay flaw exists when the design of the product makes it possible for a malicious user to sniff network traffic and bypass authentication by replaying it to the server in question to the same effect as the original message (or with minor changes).

Base CWE-295.name: Improper Certificate Validation
Base CWE-295.description: The product does not validate, or incorrectly validates, a certificate.

Base CWE-301.name: Reflection Attack in an Authentication Protocol
Base CWE-301.description: Simple authentication protocols are subject to reflection attacks if a malicious user can use the target machine to impersonate a trusted user.

Base CWE-303.name: Incorrect Implementation of Authentication Algorithm
Base CWE-303.description: The requirements for the product dictate the use of an established authentication algorithm, but the implementation of the algorithm is incorrect.

Base CWE-305.name: Authentication Bypass by Primary Weakness
Base CWE-305.description: The authentication algorithm is sound, but the implemented mechanism can be bypassed as the result of a separate weakness that is primary to the authentication error.

Base CWE-306.name: Missing Authentication for Critical Function
Base CWE-306.description: The product does not perform any authentication for functionality that requires a provable user identity or consumes a significant amount of resources.

Base CWE-307.name: Improper Restriction of Excessive Authentication Attempts
Base CWE-307.description: The product does not implement sufficient measures to prevent multiple failed authentication attempts within a short time frame, making it more susceptible to brute force attacks.

Base CWE-308.name: Use of Single-factor Authentication
Base CWE-308.description: The use of single-factor authentication can lead to unnecessary risk of compromise when compared with the benefits of a dual-factor authentication scheme.

Base CWE-309.name: Use of Password System for Primary Authentication
Base CWE-309.description: The use of password systems as the primary means of authentication may be subject to several flaws or shortcomings, each reducing the effectiveness of the mechanism.

Base CWE-312.name: Cleartext Storage of Sensitive Information
Base CWE-312.description: The product stores sensitive information in cleartext within a resource that might be accessible to another control sphere.

Base CWE-319.name: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information
Base CWE-319.description: The product transmits sensitive or security-critical data in cleartext in a communication channel that can be sniffed by unauthorized actors.

Base CWE-322.name: Key Exchange without Entity Authentication
Base CWE-322.description: The product performs a key exchange with an actor without verifying the identity of that actor.

Base CWE-323.name: Reusing a Nonce, Key Pair in Encryption
Base CWE-323.description: Nonces should be used for the present occasion and only once.

Base CWE-324.name: Use of a Key Past its Expiration Date
Base CWE-324.description: The product uses a cryptographic key or password past its expiration date, which diminishes its safety significantly by increasing the timing window for cracking attacks against that key.

Base CWE-325.name: Missing Cryptographic Step
Base CWE-325.description: The product does not implement a required step in a cryptographic algorithm, resulting in weaker encryption than advertised by the algorithm.

Base CWE-328.name: Use of Weak Hash
Base CWE-328.description: The product uses an algorithm that produces a digest (output value) that does not meet security expectations for a hash function that allows an adversary to reasonably determine the original input (preimage attack), find another input that can produce the same hash (2nd preimage attack), or find multiple inputs that evaluate to the same hash (birthday attack).

Base CWE-331.name: Insufficient Entropy
Base CWE-331.description: The product uses an algorithm or scheme that produces insufficient entropy, leaving patterns or clusters of values that are more likely to occur than others.

Base CWE-334.name: Small Space of Random Values
Base CWE-334.description: The number of possible random values is smaller than needed by the product, making it more susceptible to brute force attacks.

Base CWE-335.name: Incorrect Usage of Seeds in Pseudo-Random Number Generator (PRNG)
Base CWE-335.description: The product uses a Pseudo-Random Number Generator (PRNG) but does not correctly manage seeds.

Base CWE-338.name: Use of Cryptographically Weak Pseudo-Random Number Generator (PRNG)
Base CWE-338.description: The product uses a Pseudo-Random Number Generator (PRNG) in a security context, but the PRNG's algorithm is not cryptographically strong.

Base CWE-341.name: Predictable from Observable State
Base CWE-341.description: A number or object is predictable based on observations that the attacker can make about the state of the system or network, such as time, process ID, etc.

Base CWE-342.name: Predictable Exact Value from Previous Values
Base CWE-342.description: An exact value or random number can be precisely predicted by observing previous values.

Base CWE-343.name: Predictable Value Range from Previous Values
Base CWE-343.description: The product's random number generator produces a series of values which, when observed, can be used to infer a relatively small range of possibilities for the next value that could be generated.

Base CWE-344.name: Use of Invariant Value in Dynamically Changing Context
Base CWE-344.description: The product uses a constant value, name, or reference, but this value can (or should) vary across different environments.

Class CWE-346.name: Origin Validation Error
Class CWE-346.description: The product does not properly verify that the source of data or communication is valid.

Base CWE-347.name: Improper Verification of Cryptographic Signature
Base CWE-347.description: The product does not verify, or incorrectly verifies, the cryptographic signature for data.

Base CWE-348.name: Use of Less Trusted Source
Base CWE-348.description: The product has two different sources of the same data or information, but it uses the source that has less support for verification, is less trusted, or is less resistant to attack.

Base CWE-349.name: Acceptance of Extraneous Untrusted Data With Trusted Data
Base CWE-349.description: The product, when processing trusted data, accepts any untrusted data that is also included with the trusted data, treating the untrusted data as if it were trusted.

Base CWE-351.name: Insufficient Type Distinction
Base CWE-351.description: The product does not properly distinguish between different types of elements in a way that leads to insecure behavior.

Base CWE-353.name: Missing Support for Integrity Check
Base CWE-353.description: The product uses a transmission protocol that does not include a mechanism for verifying the integrity of the data during transmission, such as a checksum.

Base CWE-354.name: Improper Validation of Integrity Check Value
Base CWE-354.description: The product does not validate or incorrectly validates the integrity check values or checksums of a message. This may prevent it from detecting if the data has been modified or corrupted in transmission.

Base CWE-356.name: Product UI does not Warn User of Unsafe Actions
Base CWE-356.description: The product's user interface does not warn the user before undertaking an unsafe action on behalf of that user. This makes it easier for attackers to trick users into inflicting damage to their system.

Base CWE-357.name: Insufficient UI Warning of Dangerous Operations
Base CWE-357.description: The user interface provides a warning to a user regarding dangerous or sensitive operations, but the warning is not noticeable enough to warrant attention.

Base CWE-358.name: Improperly Implemented Security Check for Standard
Base CWE-358.description: The product does not implement or incorrectly implements one or more security-relevant checks as specified by the design of a standardized algorithm, protocol, or technique.

Base CWE-359.name: Exposure of Private Personal Information to an Unauthorized Actor
Base CWE-359.description: The product does not properly prevent a person's private, personal information from being accessed by actors who either (1) are not explicitly authorized to access the information or (2) do not have the implicit consent of the person about whom the information is collected.

Base CWE-360.name: Trust of System Event Data
Base CWE-360.description: Security based on event locations are insecure and can be spoofed.

Base CWE-364.name: Signal Handler Race Condition
Base CWE-364.description: The product uses a signal handler that introduces a race condition.

Base CWE-366.name: Race Condition within a Thread
Base CWE-366.description: If two threads of execution use a resource simultaneously, there exists the possibility that resources may be used while invalid, in turn making the state of execution undefined.

Base CWE-367.name: Time-of-check Time-of-use (TOCTOU) Race Condition
Base CWE-367.description: The product checks the state of a resource before using that resource, but the resource's state can change between the check and the use in a way that invalidates the results of the check. This can cause the product to perform invalid actions when the resource is in an unexpected state.

Base CWE-368.name: Context Switching Race Condition
Base CWE-368.description: A product performs a series of non-atomic actions to switch between contexts that cross privilege or other security boundaries, but a race condition allows an attacker to modify or misrepresent the product's behavior during the switch.

Base CWE-369.name: Divide By Zero
Base CWE-369.description: The product divides a value by zero.

Base CWE-372.name: Incomplete Internal State Distinction
Base CWE-372.description: The product does not properly determine which state it is in, causing it to assume it is in state X when in fact it is in state Y, causing it to perform incorrect operations in a security-relevant manner.

Base CWE-374.name: Passing Mutable Objects to an Untrusted Method
Base CWE-374.description: The product sends non-cloned mutable data as an argument to a method or function.

Base CWE-375.name: Returning a Mutable Object to an Untrusted Caller
Base CWE-375.description: Sending non-cloned mutable data as a return value may result in that data being altered or deleted by the calling function.

Base CWE-378.name: Creation of Temporary File With Insecure Permissions
Base CWE-378.description: Opening temporary files without appropriate measures or controls can leave the file, its contents and any function that it impacts vulnerable to attack.

Base CWE-379.name: Creation of Temporary File in Directory with Insecure Permissions
Base CWE-379.description: The product creates a temporary file in a directory whose permissions allow unintended actors to determine the file's existence or otherwise access that file.

Base CWE-385.name: Covert Timing Channel
Base CWE-385.description: Covert timing channels convey information by modulating some aspect of system behavior over time, so that the program receiving the information can observe system behavior and infer protected information.

Base CWE-386.name: Symbolic Name not Mapping to Correct Object
Base CWE-386.description: A constant symbolic reference to an object is used, even though the reference can resolve to a different object over time.

Base CWE-390.name: Detection of Error Condition Without Action
Base CWE-390.description: The product detects a specific error, but takes no actions to handle the error.

Base CWE-391.name: Unchecked Error Condition
Base CWE-391.description: [PLANNED FOR DEPRECATION. SEE MAINTENANCE NOTES AND CONSIDER CWE-252, CWE-248, OR CWE-1069.] Ignoring exceptions and other error conditions may allow an attacker to induce unexpected behavior unnoticed.

Base CWE-392.name: Missing Report of Error Condition
Base CWE-392.description: The product encounters an error but does not provide a status code or return value to indicate that an error has occurred.

Base CWE-393.name: Return of Wrong Status Code
Base CWE-393.description: A function or operation returns an incorrect return value or status code that does not indicate an error, but causes the product to modify its behavior based on the incorrect result.

Base CWE-394.name: Unexpected Status Code or Return Value
Base CWE-394.description: The product does not properly check when a function or operation returns a value that is legitimate for the function, but is not expected by the product.

Base CWE-395.name: Use of NullPointerException Catch to Detect NULL Pointer Dereference
Base CWE-395.description: Catching NullPointerException should not be used as an alternative to programmatic checks to prevent dereferencing a null pointer.

Base CWE-396.name: Declaration of Catch for Generic Exception
Base CWE-396.description: Catching overly broad exceptions promotes complex error handling code that is more likely to contain security vulnerabilities.

Base CWE-397.name: Declaration of Throws for Generic Exception
Base CWE-397.description: Throwing overly broad exceptions promotes complex error handling code that is more likely to contain security vulnerabilities.

Base CWE-403.name: Exposure of File Descriptor to Unintended Control Sphere ('File Descriptor Leak')
Base CWE-403.description: A process does not close sensitive file descriptors before invoking a child process, which allows the child to perform unauthorized I/O operations using those descriptors.

Base CWE-408.name: Incorrect Behavior Order: Early Amplification
Base CWE-408.description: The product allows an entity to perform a legitimate but expensive operation before authentication or authorization has taken place.

Base CWE-409.name: Improper Handling of Highly Compressed Data (Data Amplification)
Base CWE-409.description: The product does not handle or incorrectly handles a compressed input with a very high compression ratio that produces a large output.

Base CWE-410.name: Insufficient Resource Pool
Base CWE-410.description: The product's resource pool is not large enough to handle peak demand, which allows an attacker to prevent others from accessing the resource by using a (relatively) large number of requests for resources.

Base CWE-412.name: Unrestricted Externally Accessible Lock
Base CWE-412.description: The product properly checks for the existence of a lock, but the lock can be externally controlled or influenced by an actor that is outside of the intended sphere of control.

Base CWE-413.name: Improper Resource Locking
Base CWE-413.description: The product does not lock or does not correctly lock a resource when the product must have exclusive access to the resource.

Base CWE-414.name: Missing Lock Check
Base CWE-414.description: A product does not check to see if a lock is present before performing sensitive operations on a resource.

Base CWE-419.name: Unprotected Primary Channel
Base CWE-419.description: The product uses a primary channel for administration or restricted functionality, but it does not properly protect the channel.

Base CWE-420.name: Unprotected Alternate Channel
Base CWE-420.description: The product protects a primary channel, but it does not use the same level of protection for an alternate channel.

Base CWE-421.name: Race Condition During Access to Alternate Channel
Base CWE-421.description: The product opens an alternate channel to communicate with an authorized user, but the channel is accessible to other actors.

Base CWE-425.name: Direct Request ('Forced Browsing')
Base CWE-425.description: The web application does not adequately enforce appropriate authorization on all restricted URLs, scripts, or files.

Base CWE-426.name: Untrusted Search Path
Base CWE-426.description: The product searches for critical resources using an externally-supplied search path that can point to resources that are not under the product's direct control.

Base CWE-427.name: Uncontrolled Search Path Element
Base CWE-427.description: The product uses a fixed or controlled search path to find resources, but one or more locations in that path can be under the control of unintended actors.

Base CWE-428.name: Unquoted Search Path or Element
Base CWE-428.description: The product uses a search path that contains an unquoted element, in which the element contains whitespace or other separators. This can cause the product to access resources in a parent path.

Base CWE-430.name: Deployment of Wrong Handler
Base CWE-430.description: The wrong handler is assigned to process an object.

Base CWE-431.name: Missing Handler
Base CWE-431.description: A handler is not available or implemented.

Base CWE-434.name: Unrestricted Upload of File with Dangerous Type
Base CWE-434.description: The product allows the attacker to upload or transfer files of dangerous types that can be automatically processed within the product's environment.

Base CWE-437.name: Incomplete Model of Endpoint Features
Base CWE-437.description: A product acts as an intermediary or monitor between two or more endpoints, but it does not have a complete model of an endpoint's features, behaviors, or state, potentially causing the product to perform incorrect actions based on this incomplete model.

Base CWE-439.name: Behavioral Change in New Version or Environment
Base CWE-439.description: A's behavior or functionality changes with a new version of A, or a new environment, which is not known (or manageable) by B.

Base CWE-440.name: Expected Behavior Violation
Base CWE-440.description: A feature, API, or function does not perform according to its specification.

Base CWE-444.name: Inconsistent Interpretation of HTTP Requests ('HTTP Request/Response Smuggling')
Base CWE-444.description: The product acts as an intermediary HTTP agent (such as a proxy or firewall) in the data flow between two entities such as a client and server, but it does not interpret malformed HTTP requests or responses in ways that are consistent with how the messages will be processed by those entities that are at the ultimate destination.

Base CWE-447.name: Unimplemented or Unsupported Feature in UI
Base CWE-447.description: A UI function for a security feature appears to be supported and gives feedback to the user that suggests that it is supported, but the underlying functionality is not implemented.

Base CWE-448.name: Obsolete Feature in UI
Base CWE-448.description: A UI function is obsolete and the product does not warn the user.

Base CWE-449.name: The UI Performs the Wrong Action
Base CWE-449.description: The UI performs the wrong action with respect to the user's request.

Base CWE-454.name: External Initialization of Trusted Variables or Data Stores
Base CWE-454.description: The product initializes critical internal variables or data stores using inputs that can be modified by untrusted actors.

Base CWE-455.name: Non-exit on Failed Initialization
Base CWE-455.description: The product does not exit or otherwise modify its operation when security-relevant errors occur during initialization, such as when a configuration file has a format error or a hardware security module (HSM) cannot be activated, which can cause the product to execute in a less secure fashion than intended by the administrator.

Base CWE-459.name: Incomplete Cleanup
Base CWE-459.description: The product does not properly clean up and remove temporary or supporting resources after they have been used.

Base CWE-463.name: Deletion of Data Structure Sentinel
Base CWE-463.description: The accidental deletion of a data-structure sentinel can cause serious programming logic problems.

Base CWE-464.name: Addition of Data Structure Sentinel
Base CWE-464.description: The accidental addition of a data-structure sentinel can cause serious programming logic problems.

Base CWE-466.name: Return of Pointer Value Outside of Expected Range
Base CWE-466.description: A function can return a pointer to memory that is outside of the buffer that the pointer is expected to reference.

Base CWE-468.name: Incorrect Pointer Scaling
Base CWE-468.description: In C and C++, one may often accidentally refer to the wrong memory due to the semantics of when math operations are implicitly scaled.

Base CWE-469.name: Use of Pointer Subtraction to Determine Size
Base CWE-469.description: The product subtracts one pointer from another in order to determine size, but this calculation can be incorrect if the pointers do not exist in the same memory chunk.

Base CWE-470.name: Use of Externally-Controlled Input to Select Classes or Code ('Unsafe Reflection')
Base CWE-470.description: The product uses external input with reflection to select which classes or code to use, but it does not sufficiently prevent the input from selecting improper classes or code.

Base CWE-472.name: External Control of Assumed-Immutable Web Parameter
Base CWE-472.description: The web application does not sufficiently verify inputs that are assumed to be immutable but are actually externally controllable, such as hidden form fields.

Base CWE-474.name: Use of Function with Inconsistent Implementations
Base CWE-474.description: The code uses a function that has inconsistent implementations across operating systems and versions.

Base CWE-475.name: Undefined Behavior for Input to API
Base CWE-475.description: The behavior of this function is undefined unless its control parameter is set to a specific value.

Base CWE-476.name: NULL Pointer Dereference
Base CWE-476.description: A NULL pointer dereference occurs when the application dereferences a pointer that it expects to be valid, but is NULL, typically causing a crash or exit.

Base CWE-477.name: Use of Obsolete Function
Base CWE-477.description: The code uses deprecated or obsolete functions, which suggests that the code has not been actively reviewed or maintained.

Base CWE-478.name: Missing Default Case in Multiple Condition Expression
Base CWE-478.description: The code does not have a default case in an expression with multiple conditions, such as a switch statement.

Base CWE-480.name: Use of Incorrect Operator
Base CWE-480.description: The product accidentally uses the wrong operator, which changes the logic in security-relevant ways.

Base CWE-483.name: Incorrect Block Delimitation
Base CWE-483.description: The code does not explicitly delimit a block that is intended to contain 2 or more statements, creating a logic error.

Base CWE-484.name: Omitted Break Statement in Switch
Base CWE-484.description: The product omits a break statement within a switch or similar construct, causing code associated with multiple conditions to execute. This can cause problems when the programmer only intended to execute code associated with one condition.

Base CWE-487.name: Reliance on Package-level Scope
Base CWE-487.description: Java packages are not inherently closed; therefore, relying on them for code security is not a good practice.

Base CWE-488.name: Exposure of Data Element to Wrong Session
Base CWE-488.description: The product does not sufficiently enforce boundaries between the states of different sessions, causing data to be provided to, or used by, the wrong session.

Base CWE-489.name: Active Debug Code
Base CWE-489.description: The product is deployed to unauthorized actors with debugging code still enabled or active, which can create unintended entry points or expose sensitive information.

Base CWE-494.name: Download of Code Without Integrity Check
Base CWE-494.description: The product downloads source code or an executable from a remote location and executes the code without sufficiently verifying the origin and integrity of the code.

Base CWE-497.name: Exposure of Sensitive System Information to an Unauthorized Control Sphere
Base CWE-497.description: The product does not properly prevent sensitive system-level information from being accessed by unauthorized actors who do not have the same level of access to the underlying system as the product does.

Base CWE-501.name: Trust Boundary Violation
Base CWE-501.description: The product mixes trusted and untrusted data in the same data structure or structured message.

Base CWE-502.name: Deserialization of Untrusted Data
Base CWE-502.description: The product deserializes untrusted data without sufficiently verifying that the resulting data will be valid.

Base CWE-515.name: Covert Storage Channel
Base CWE-515.description: A covert storage channel transfers information through the setting of bits by one program and the reading of those bits by another. What distinguishes this case from that of ordinary operation is that the bits are used to convey encoded information.

Base CWE-521.name: Weak Password Requirements
Base CWE-521.description: The product does not require that users should have strong passwords, which makes it easier for attackers to compromise user accounts.

Base CWE-523.name: Unprotected Transport of Credentials
Base CWE-523.description: Login pages do not use adequate measures to protect the user name and password while they are in transit from the client to the server.

Base CWE-524.name: Use of Cache Containing Sensitive Information
Base CWE-524.description: The code uses a cache that contains sensitive information, but the cache can be read by an actor outside of the intended control sphere.

Base CWE-538.name: Insertion of Sensitive Information into Externally-Accessible File or Directory
Base CWE-538.description: The product places sensitive information into files or directories that are accessible to actors who are allowed to have access to the files, but not to the sensitive information.

Base CWE-544.name: Missing Standardized Error Handling Mechanism
Base CWE-544.description: The product does not use a standardized method for handling errors throughout the code, which might introduce inconsistent error handling and resultant weaknesses.

Base CWE-547.name: Use of Hard-coded, Security-relevant Constants
Base CWE-547.description: The product uses hard-coded constants instead of symbolic names for security-critical values, which increases the likelihood of mistakes during code maintenance or security policy change.

Base CWE-549.name: Missing Password Field Masking
Base CWE-549.description: The product does not mask passwords during entry, increasing the potential for attackers to observe and capture passwords.

Base CWE-551.name: Incorrect Behavior Order: Authorization Before Parsing and Canonicalization
Base CWE-551.description: If a web server does not fully parse requested URLs before it examines them for authorization, it may be possible for an attacker to bypass authorization protection.

Base CWE-552.name: Files or Directories Accessible to External Parties
Base CWE-552.description: The product makes files or directories accessible to unauthorized actors, even though they should not be.

Base CWE-561.name: Dead Code
Base CWE-561.description: The product contains dead code, which can never be executed.

Base CWE-562.name: Return of Stack Variable Address
Base CWE-562.description: A function returns the address of a stack variable, which will cause unintended program behavior, typically in the form of a crash.

Base CWE-563.name: Assignment to Variable without Use
Base CWE-563.description: The variable's value is assigned but never used, making it a dead store.

Base CWE-565.name: Reliance on Cookies without Validation and Integrity Checking
Base CWE-565.description: The product relies on the existence or values of cookies when performing security-critical operations, but it does not properly ensure that the setting is valid for the associated user.

Base CWE-570.name: Expression is Always False
Base CWE-570.description: The product contains an expression that will always evaluate to false.

Base CWE-571.name: Expression is Always True
Base CWE-571.description: The product contains an expression that will always evaluate to true.

Variant CWE-580.name: clone() Method Without super.clone()
Variant CWE-580.description: The product contains a clone() method that does not call super.clone() to obtain the new object.

Base CWE-581.name: Object Model Violation: Just One of Equals and Hashcode Defined
Base CWE-581.description: The product does not maintain equal hashcodes for equal objects.

Base CWE-584.name: Return Inside Finally Block
Base CWE-584.description: The code has a return statement inside a finally block, which will cause any thrown exception in the try block to be discarded.

Base CWE-586.name: Explicit Call to Finalize()
Base CWE-586.description: The product makes an explicit call to the finalize() method from outside the finalizer.

Variant CWE-587.name: Assignment of a Fixed Address to a Pointer
Variant CWE-587.description: The product sets a pointer to a specific address other than NULL or 0.

Base CWE-601.name: URL Redirection to Untrusted Site ('Open Redirect')
Base CWE-601.description: A web application accepts a user-controlled input that specifies a link to an external site, and uses that link in a Redirect. This simplifies phishing attacks.

Base CWE-603.name: Use of Client-Side Authentication
Base CWE-603.description: A client/server product performs authentication within client code but not in server code, allowing server-side authentication to be bypassed via a modified client that omits the authentication check.

Base CWE-605.name: Multiple Binds to the Same Port
Base CWE-605.description: When multiple sockets are allowed to bind to the same port, other services on that port may be stolen or spoofed.

Base CWE-606.name: Unchecked Input for Loop Condition
Base CWE-606.description: The product does not properly check inputs that are used for loop conditions, potentially leading to a denial of service or other consequences because of excessive looping.

Base CWE-609.name: Double-Checked Locking
Base CWE-609.description: The product uses double-checked locking to access a resource without the overhead of explicit synchronization, but the locking is insufficient.

Base CWE-611.name: Improper Restriction of XML External Entity Reference
Base CWE-611.description: The product processes an XML document that can contain XML entities with URIs that resolve to documents outside of the intended sphere of control, causing the product to embed incorrect documents into its output.

Base CWE-613.name: Insufficient Session Expiration
Base CWE-613.description: According to WASC, Insufficient Session Expiration is when a web site permits an attacker to reuse old session credentials or session IDs for authorization.

Base CWE-617.name: Reachable Assertion
Base CWE-617.description: The product contains an assert() or similar statement that can be triggered by an attacker, which leads to an application exit or other behavior that is more severe than necessary.

Variant CWE-618.name: Exposed Unsafe ActiveX Method
Variant CWE-618.description: An ActiveX control is intended for use in a web browser, but it exposes dangerous methods that perform actions that are outside of the browser's security model (e.g. the zone or domain).

Base CWE-619.name: Dangling Database Cursor ('Cursor Injection')
Base CWE-619.description: If a database cursor is not closed properly, then it could become accessible to other users while retaining the same privileges that were originally assigned, leaving the cursor dangling.

Base CWE-620.name: Unverified Password Change
Base CWE-620.description: When setting a new password for a user, the product does not require knowledge of the original password, or using another form of authentication.

Base CWE-624.name: Executable Regular Expression Error
Base CWE-624.description: The product uses a regular expression that either (1) contains an executable component with user-controlled inputs, or (2) allows a user to enable execution by inserting pattern modifiers.

Base CWE-625.name: Permissive Regular Expression
Base CWE-625.description: The product uses a regular expression that does not sufficiently restrict the set of allowed values.

Base CWE-628.name: Function Call with Incorrectly Specified Arguments
Base CWE-628.description: The product calls a function, procedure, or routine with arguments that are not correctly specified, leading to always-incorrect behavior and resultant weaknesses.

Base CWE-639.name: Authorization Bypass Through User-Controlled Key
Base CWE-639.description: The system's authorization functionality does not prevent one user from gaining access to another user's data or record by modifying the key value identifying the data.

Base CWE-640.name: Weak Password Recovery Mechanism for Forgotten Password
Base CWE-640.description: The product contains a mechanism for users to recover or change their passwords without knowing the original password, but the mechanism is weak.

Base CWE-641.name: Improper Restriction of Names for Files and Other Resources
Base CWE-641.description: The product constructs the name of a file or other resource using input from an upstream component, but it does not restrict or incorrectly restricts the resulting name.

Base CWE-645.name: Overly Restrictive Account Lockout Mechanism
Base CWE-645.description: The product contains an account lockout protection mechanism, but the mechanism is too restrictive and can be triggered too easily, which allows attackers to deny service to legitimate users by causing their accounts to be locked out.

Base CWE-648.name: Incorrect Use of Privileged APIs
Base CWE-648.description: The product does not conform to the API requirements for a function call that requires extra privileges. This could allow attackers to gain privileges by causing the function to be called incorrectly.

Base CWE-649.name: Reliance on Obfuscation or Encryption of Security-Relevant Inputs without Integrity Checking
Base CWE-649.description: The product uses obfuscation or encryption of inputs that should not be mutable by an external actor, but the product does not use integrity checks to detect if those inputs have been modified.

Base CWE-653.name: Improper Isolation or Compartmentalization
Base CWE-653.description: The product does not properly compartmentalize or isolate functionality, processes, or resources that require different privilege levels, rights, or permissions.

Base CWE-654.name: Reliance on a Single Factor in a Security Decision
Base CWE-654.description: A protection mechanism relies exclusively, or to a large extent, on the evaluation of a single condition or the integrity of a single object or entity in order to make a decision about granting access to restricted resources or functionality.

Class CWE-656.name: Reliance on Security Through Obscurity
Class CWE-656.description: The product uses a protection mechanism whose strength depends heavily on its obscurity, such that knowledge of its algorithms or key data is sufficient to defeat the mechanism.

Base CWE-663.name: Use of a Non-reentrant Function in a Concurrent Context
Base CWE-663.description: The product calls a non-reentrant function in a concurrent context in which a competing code sequence (e.g. thread or signal handler) may have an opportunity to call the same function or otherwise influence its state.

Base CWE-676.name: Use of Potentially Dangerous Function
Base CWE-676.description: The product invokes a potentially dangerous function that could introduce a vulnerability if it is used incorrectly, but the function can also be used safely.

Base CWE-681.name: Incorrect Conversion between Numeric Types
Base CWE-681.description: When converting from one data type to another, such as long to integer, data can be omitted or translated in a way that produces unexpected values. If the resulting values are used in a sensitive context, then dangerous behaviors may occur.

Base CWE-694.name: Use of Multiple Resources with Duplicate Identifier
Base CWE-694.description: The product uses multiple resources that can have the same identifier, in a context in which unique identifiers are required.

Base CWE-695.name: Use of Low-Level Functionality
Base CWE-695.description: The product uses low-level functionality that is explicitly prohibited by the framework or specification under which the product is supposed to operate.

Base CWE-698.name: Execution After Redirect (EAR)
Base CWE-698.description: The web application sends a redirect to another location, but instead of exiting, it executes additional code.

Base CWE-708.name: Incorrect Ownership Assignment
Base CWE-708.description: The product assigns an owner to a resource, but the owner is outside of the intended control sphere.

Base CWE-733.name: Compiler Optimization Removal or Modification of Security-critical Code
Base CWE-733.description: The developer builds a security-critical protection mechanism into the software, but the compiler optimizes the program such that the mechanism is removed or modified.

Base CWE-749.name: Exposed Dangerous Method or Function
Base CWE-749.description: The product provides an Applications Programming Interface (API) or similar interface for interaction with external actors, but the interface includes a dangerous method or function that is not properly restricted.

Base CWE-756.name: Missing Custom Error Page
Base CWE-756.description: The product does not return custom error pages to the user, possibly exposing sensitive information.

Base CWE-763.name: Release of Invalid Pointer or Reference
Base CWE-763.description: The product attempts to return a memory resource to the system, but it calls the wrong release function or calls the appropriate release function incorrectly.

Base CWE-764.name: Multiple Locks of a Critical Resource
Base CWE-764.description: The product locks a critical resource more times than intended, leading to an unexpected state in the system.

Base CWE-765.name: Multiple Unlocks of a Critical Resource
Base CWE-765.description: The product unlocks a critical resource more times than intended, leading to an unexpected state in the system.

Base CWE-766.name: Critical Data Element Declared Public
Base CWE-766.description: The product declares a critical variable, field, or member to be public when intended security policy requires it to be private.

Base CWE-767.name: Access to Critical Private Variable via Public Method
Base CWE-767.description: The product defines a public method that reads or modifies a private variable.

Base CWE-770.name: Allocation of Resources Without Limits or Throttling
Base CWE-770.description: The product allocates a reusable resource or group of resources on behalf of an actor without imposing any restrictions on the size or number of resources that can be allocated, in violation of the intended security policy for that actor.

Base CWE-771.name: Missing Reference to Active Allocated Resource
Base CWE-771.description: The product does not properly maintain a reference to a resource that has been allocated, which prevents the resource from being reclaimed.

Base CWE-772.name: Missing Release of Resource after Effective Lifetime
Base CWE-772.description: The product does not release a resource after its effective lifetime has ended, i.e., after the resource is no longer needed.

Base CWE-776.name: Improper Restriction of Recursive Entity References in DTDs ('XML Entity Expansion')
Base CWE-776.description: The product uses XML documents and allows their structure to be defined with a Document Type Definition (DTD), but it does not properly control the number of recursive definitions of entities.

Base CWE-778.name: Insufficient Logging
Base CWE-778.description: When a security-critical event occurs, the product either does not record the event or omits important details about the event when logging it.

Base CWE-779.name: Logging of Excessive Data
Base CWE-779.description: The product logs too much information, making log files hard to process and possibly hindering recovery efforts or forensic analysis after an attack.

Base CWE-783.name: Operator Precedence Logic Error
Base CWE-783.description: The product uses an expression in which operator precedence causes incorrect logic to be used.

Base CWE-786.name: Access of Memory Location Before Start of Buffer
Base CWE-786.description: The product reads or writes to a buffer using an index or pointer that references a memory location prior to the beginning of the buffer.

Base CWE-787.name: Out-of-bounds Write
Base CWE-787.description: The product writes data past the end, or before the beginning, of the intended buffer.

Base CWE-788.name: Access of Memory Location After End of Buffer
Base CWE-788.description: The product reads or writes to a buffer using an index or pointer that references a memory location after the end of the buffer.

Base CWE-791.name: Incomplete Filtering of Special Elements
Base CWE-791.description: The product receives data from an upstream component, but does not completely filter special elements before sending it to a downstream component.

Base CWE-798.name: Use of Hard-coded Credentials
Base CWE-798.description: The product contains hard-coded credentials, such as a password or cryptographic key, which it uses for its own inbound authentication, outbound communication to external components, or encryption of internal data.

Base CWE-804.name: Guessable CAPTCHA
Base CWE-804.description: The product uses a CAPTCHA challenge, but the challenge can be guessed or automatically recognized by a non-human actor.

Base CWE-805.name: Buffer Access with Incorrect Length Value
Base CWE-805.description: The product uses a sequential operation to read or write a buffer, but it uses an incorrect length value that causes it to access memory that is outside of the bounds of the buffer.

Base CWE-807.name: Reliance on Untrusted Inputs in a Security Decision
Base CWE-807.description: The product uses a protection mechanism that relies on the existence or values of an input, but the input can be modified by an untrusted actor in a way that bypasses the protection mechanism.

Base CWE-820.name: Missing Synchronization
Base CWE-820.description: The product utilizes a shared resource in a concurrent manner but does not attempt to synchronize access to the resource.

Base CWE-821.name: Incorrect Synchronization
Base CWE-821.description: The product utilizes a shared resource in a concurrent manner, but it does not correctly synchronize access to the resource.

Base CWE-822.name: Untrusted Pointer Dereference
Base CWE-822.description: The product obtains a value from an untrusted source, converts this value to a pointer, and dereferences the resulting pointer.

Base CWE-823.name: Use of Out-of-range Pointer Offset
Base CWE-823.description: The product performs pointer arithmetic on a valid pointer, but it uses an offset that can point outside of the intended range of valid memory locations for the resulting pointer.

Base CWE-824.name: Access of Uninitialized Pointer
Base CWE-824.description: The product accesses or uses a pointer that has not been initialized.

Base CWE-825.name: Expired Pointer Dereference
Base CWE-825.description: The product dereferences a pointer that contains a location for memory that was previously valid, but is no longer valid.

Base CWE-826.name: Premature Release of Resource During Expected Lifetime
Base CWE-826.description: The product releases a resource that is still intended to be used by itself or another actor.

Base CWE-829.name: Inclusion of Functionality from Untrusted Control Sphere
Base CWE-829.description: The product imports, requires, or includes executable functionality (such as a library) from a source that is outside of the intended control sphere.

Base CWE-832.name: Unlock of a Resource that is not Locked
Base CWE-832.description: The product attempts to unlock a resource that is not locked.

Base CWE-833.name: Deadlock
Base CWE-833.description: The product contains multiple threads or executable segments that are waiting for each other to release a necessary lock, resulting in deadlock.

Base CWE-835.name: Loop with Unreachable Exit Condition ('Infinite Loop')
Base CWE-835.description: The product contains an iteration or loop with an exit condition that cannot be reached, i.e., an infinite loop.

Base CWE-836.name: Use of Password Hash Instead of Password for Authentication
Base CWE-836.description: The product records password hashes in a data store, receives a hash of a password from a client, and compares the supplied hash to the hash obtained from the data store.

Base CWE-837.name: Improper Enforcement of a Single, Unique Action
Base CWE-837.description: The product requires that an actor should only be able to perform an action once, or to have only one unique action, but the product does not enforce or improperly enforces this restriction.

Base CWE-838.name: Inappropriate Encoding for Output Context
Base CWE-838.description: The product uses or specifies an encoding when generating output to a downstream component, but the specified encoding is not the same as the encoding that is expected by the downstream component.

Base CWE-839.name: Numeric Range Comparison Without Minimum Check
Base CWE-839.description: The product checks a value to ensure that it is less than or equal to a maximum, but it does not also verify that the value is greater than or equal to the minimum.

Base CWE-841.name: Improper Enforcement of Behavioral Workflow
Base CWE-841.description: The product supports a session in which more than one behavior must be performed by an actor, but it does not properly ensure that the actor performs the behaviors in the required sequence.

Base CWE-842.name: Placement of User into Incorrect Group
Base CWE-842.description: The product or the administrator places a user into an incorrect group.

Base CWE-843.name: Access of Resource Using Incompatible Type ('Type Confusion')
Base CWE-843.description: The product allocates or initializes a resource such as a pointer, object, or variable using one type, but it later accesses that resource using a type that is incompatible with the original type.

Base CWE-908.name: Use of Uninitialized Resource
Base CWE-908.description: The product uses or accesses a resource that has not been initialized.

Base CWE-909.name: Missing Initialization of Resource
Base CWE-909.description: The product does not initialize a critical resource.

Base CWE-910.name: Use of Expired File Descriptor
Base CWE-910.description: The product uses or accesses a file descriptor after it has been closed.

Base CWE-911.name: Improper Update of Reference Count
Base CWE-911.description: The product uses a reference count to manage a resource, but it does not update or incorrectly updates the reference count.

Base CWE-914.name: Improper Control of Dynamically-Identified Variables
Base CWE-914.description: The product does not properly restrict reading from or writing to dynamically-identified variables.

Base CWE-915.name: Improperly Controlled Modification of Dynamically-Determined Object Attributes
Base CWE-915.description: The product receives input from an upstream component that specifies multiple attributes, properties, or fields that are to be initialized or updated in an object, but it does not properly control which attributes can be modified.

Base CWE-916.name: Use of Password Hash With Insufficient Computational Effort
Base CWE-916.description: The product generates a hash for a password, but it uses a scheme that does not provide a sufficient level of computational effort that would make password cracking attacks infeasible or expensive.

Base CWE-917.name: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an Expression Language Statement ('Expression Language Injection')
Base CWE-917.description: The product constructs all or part of an expression language (EL) statement in a framework such as a Java Server Page (JSP) using externally-influenced input from an upstream component, but it does not neutralize or incorrectly neutralizes special elements that could modify the intended EL statement before it is executed.

Base CWE-918.name: Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)
Base CWE-918.description: The web server receives a URL or similar request from an upstream component and retrieves the contents of this URL, but it does not sufficiently ensure that the request is being sent to the expected destination.

Base CWE-920.name: Improper Restriction of Power Consumption
Base CWE-920.description: The product operates in an environment in which power is a limited resource that cannot be automatically replenished, but the product does not properly restrict the amount of power that its operation consumes.

Base CWE-921.name: Storage of Sensitive Data in a Mechanism without Access Control
Base CWE-921.description: The product stores sensitive information in a file system or device that does not have built-in access control.

Base CWE-924.name: Improper Enforcement of Message Integrity During Transmission in a Communication Channel
Base CWE-924.description: The product establishes a communication channel with an endpoint and receives a message from that endpoint, but it does not sufficiently ensure that the message was not modified during transmission.

Base CWE-939.name: Improper Authorization in Handler for Custom URL Scheme
Base CWE-939.description: The product uses a handler for a custom URL scheme, but it does not properly restrict which actors can invoke the handler using the scheme.

Base CWE-940.name: Improper Verification of Source of a Communication Channel
Base CWE-940.description: The product establishes a communication channel to handle an incoming request that has been initiated by an actor, but it does not properly verify that the request is coming from the expected origin.

Base CWE-941.name: Incorrectly Specified Destination in a Communication Channel
Base CWE-941.description: The product creates a communication channel to initiate an outgoing request to an actor, but it does not correctly specify the intended destination for that actor.

Base CWE-1007.name: Insufficient Visual Distinction of Homoglyphs Presented to User
Base CWE-1007.description: The product displays information or identifiers to a user, but the display mechanism does not make it easy for the user to distinguish between visually similar or identical glyphs (homoglyphs), which may cause the user to misinterpret a glyph and perform an unintended, insecure action.

Base CWE-1021.name: Improper Restriction of Rendered UI Layers or Frames
Base CWE-1021.description: The web application does not restrict or incorrectly restricts frame objects or UI layers that belong to another application or domain, which can lead to user confusion about which interface the user is interacting with.

Base CWE-1024.name: Comparison of Incompatible Types
Base CWE-1024.description: The product performs a comparison between two entities, but the entities are of different, incompatible types that cannot be guaranteed to provide correct results when they are directly compared.

Base CWE-1025.name: Comparison Using Wrong Factors
Base CWE-1025.description: The code performs a comparison between two entities, but the comparison examines the wrong factors or characteristics of the entities, which can lead to incorrect results and resultant weaknesses.

Base CWE-1037.name: Processor Optimization Removal or Modification of Security-critical Code
Base CWE-1037.description: The developer builds a security-critical protection mechanism into the software, but the processor optimizes the execution of the program such that the mechanism is removed or modified.

Base CWE-1041.name: Use of Redundant Code
Base CWE-1041.description: The product has multiple functions, methods, procedures, macros, etc. that contain the same code.

Base CWE-1043.name: Data Element Aggregating an Excessively Large Number of Non-Primitive Elements
Base CWE-1043.description: The product uses a data element that has an excessively large number of sub-elements with non-primitive data types such as structures or aggregated objects.

Base CWE-1044.name: Architecture with Number of Horizontal Layers Outside of Expected Range
Base CWE-1044.description: The product's architecture contains too many - or too few - horizontal layers.

Base CWE-1045.name: Parent Class with a Virtual Destructor and a Child Class without a Virtual Destructor
Base CWE-1045.description: A parent class has a virtual destructor method, but the parent has a child class that does not have a virtual destructor.

Base CWE-1046.name: Creation of Immutable Text Using String Concatenation
Base CWE-1046.description: The product creates an immutable text string using string concatenation operations.

Base CWE-1047.name: Modules with Circular Dependencies
Base CWE-1047.description: The product contains modules in which one module has references that cycle back to itself, i.e., there are circular dependencies.

Base CWE-1048.name: Invokable Control Element with Large Number of Outward Calls
Base CWE-1048.description: The code contains callable control elements that contain an excessively large number of references to other application objects external to the context of the callable, i.e. a Fan-Out value that is excessively large.

Base CWE-1049.name: Excessive Data Query Operations in a Large Data Table
Base CWE-1049.description: The product performs a data query with a large number of joins and sub-queries on a large data table.

Base CWE-1050.name: Excessive Platform Resource Consumption within a Loop
Base CWE-1050.description: The product has a loop body or loop condition that contains a control element that directly or indirectly consumes platform resources, e.g. messaging, sessions, locks, or file descriptors.

Base CWE-1051.name: Initialization with Hard-Coded Network Resource Configuration Data
Base CWE-1051.description: The product initializes data using hard-coded values that act as network resource identifiers.

Base CWE-1052.name: Excessive Use of Hard-Coded Literals in Initialization
Base CWE-1052.description: The product initializes a data element using a hard-coded literal that is not a simple integer or static constant element.

Base CWE-1053.name: Missing Documentation for Design
Base CWE-1053.description: The product does not have documentation that represents how it is designed.

Base CWE-1054.name: Invocation of a Control Element at an Unnecessarily Deep Horizontal Layer
Base CWE-1054.description: The code at one architectural layer invokes code that resides at a deeper layer than the adjacent layer, i.e., the invocation skips at least one layer, and the invoked code is not part of a vertical utility layer that can be referenced from any horizontal layer.

Base CWE-1055.name: Multiple Inheritance from Concrete Classes
Base CWE-1055.description: The product contains a class with inheritance from more than one concrete class.

Base CWE-1056.name: Invokable Control Element with Variadic Parameters
Base CWE-1056.description: A named-callable or method control element has a signature that supports a variable (variadic) number of parameters or arguments.

Base CWE-1057.name: Data Access Operations Outside of Expected Data Manager Component
Base CWE-1057.description: The product uses a dedicated, central data manager component as required by design, but it contains code that performs data-access operations that do not use this data manager.

Base CWE-1058.name: Invokable Control Element in Multi-Thread Context with non-Final Static Storable or Member Element
Base CWE-1058.description: The code contains a function or method that operates in a multi-threaded environment but owns an unsafe non-final static storable or member data element.

Base CWE-1060.name: Excessive Number of Inefficient Server-Side Data Accesses
Base CWE-1060.description: The product performs too many data queries without using efficient data processing functionality such as stored procedures.

Base CWE-1062.name: Parent Class with References to Child Class
Base CWE-1062.description: The code has a parent class that contains references to a child class, its methods, or its members.

Base CWE-1063.name: Creation of Class Instance within a Static Code Block
Base CWE-1063.description: A static code block creates an instance of a class.

Base CWE-1064.name: Invokable Control Element with Signature Containing an Excessive Number of Parameters
Base CWE-1064.description: The product contains a function, subroutine, or method whose signature has an unnecessarily large number of parameters/arguments.

Base CWE-1065.name: Runtime Resource Management Control Element in a Component Built to Run on Application Servers
Base CWE-1065.description: The product uses deployed components from application servers, but it also uses low-level functions/methods for management of resources, instead of the API provided by the application server.
